# Code owners for the high-risk paths.
#
# This plugin auto-updates from GitHub Releases with no WordPress.org review gate,
# so the release pipeline is its trust boundary: whatever ships as a release asset
# runs network-active, on every request, on every site that auto-updates. The paths
# below are the ones that can influence what ships or what executes; changes to them
# should get a maintainer's review.
#
# Enforcement: turn on "Require review from Code Owners" in the default-branch
# ruleset (see docs/SUPPLY-CHAIN-SECURITY.md). CODEOWNERS only lists the sensitive
# paths — not "*" — so routine doc/test changes are not gated, and a solo maintainer
# is not blocked from merging their own unrelated PRs.
#
# Forks: replace @dknauss with your own maintainer handle or team (e.g. @your-org/maintainers).

# The plugin's executable surface.
/force-email-two-factor.php   @dknauss
/mu-loader.php                @dknauss

# The release/CI pipeline and every Action it trusts.
/.github/                     @dknauss

# The vendored auto-updater — these bytes ship as the update payload.
/vendor/                      @dknauss

# What the release build includes/excludes and the quality/security gates.
/.gitattributes               @dknauss
/phpcs.xml.dist               @dknauss
/phpstan.neon.dist            @dknauss
/phpstan-baseline.neon        @dknauss
/phpstan/                     @dknauss
/composer.json                @dknauss
/composer.lock                @dknauss

# The definitions of the required CI checks themselves — a change here can weaken or
# skip a gate while still satisfying branch protection, so it needs the same review.
/phpunit.xml.dist             @dknauss
/bin/                         @dknauss
/playground/                  @dknauss
